  "prompt": "How does stereo differ from mono?",
  "response": "Stereo and mono refer to different methods of sound reproduction, and they differ primarily in how they create the perception of space and directionality in audio. Here\u2019s a breakdown of the key differences:\n\n### Mono (Monophonic Sound):\n1. **Single Channel**: Mono audio uses only one channel to reproduce sound. This means the same signal is sent to all speakers or headphones.\n2. **No Directionality**: Since there\u2019s only one channel, there\u2019s no spatial distinction between sounds. Everything appears to come from a single point.\n3. **Simplicity**: Mono is simpler and requires less equipment and processing power. It is often used in applications where spatial information is not important, such as in telephony, certain types of public address systems, and some older recordings.\n\n### Stereo (Stereophonic Sound):\n1. **Multiple Channels**: Stereo audio uses two channels (left and right) to create a more immersive listening experience. Different sounds can be sent to the left and right channels.\n2. **Directionality and Space**: Stereo allows for the perception of directionality and space. Sounds can be localized to different positions between the left and right speakers, creating a sense of depth and width.\n3. **Enhanced Experience**: Stereo is more complex and provides a richer, more engaging listening experience. It is commonly used in music, movies, and any application where spatial sound is important.\n\n### Key Differences:\n1. **Channel Count**: Mono uses one channel; stereo uses two.\n2. **Spatial Perception**: Mono lacks spatial distinction; stereo provides directionality and a sense of space.\n3. **Application**: Mono is used for simplicity and where spatial information is not needed; stereo is used for a more immersive and detailed sound experience.\n\n### Practical Examples:\n- **Mono**: AM radio, older telephone systems, intercoms.\n- **Stereo**: Music recordings, FM radio, modern movies, and video games.\n\nIn summary, stereo enhances the listening experience by providing a sense of space and directionality, while mono is simpler and more straightforward, suitable for situations where spatial information is not essential.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
